 <definition>
        <statement>
      <p> A function has a <term>vertical asymptote</term> at <m>x=a</m> when
<!--             <me>
    \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = + \infty
            </me> -->
    or
<!--             <me>
    \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = - \infty
            </me> -->
The limit being equal to positive infinity means that we can make the output of <m>f(x)</m> as large as we want as long as we are sufficiently close to <m>x=a</m>. Similarly, the limit being equal to negative infinity means that we can make the output of <m>f(x)</m> as small as we want as long as we are sufficiently close to <m>x=a</m>.</p>
        </statement>
    </definition>


